8 Admin commands
****************

All commands require ‘root’ or ‘casuser’.  Installed under
‘/usr/lib/casmgr/bin/’ and ‘/usr/sbin/’.

8.1 Container lifecycle
=======================

The all-in-one container is managed through systemd and Docker; there is
no dedicated container wrapper script.

     sudo systemctl start|stop|restart|status casmgr
     docker logs -f casmgr
     docker exec casmgr gosu postgres psql -U postgres -d code_analysis

   On first start the container runs ‘initdb’, creates the ‘vector’
extension, and provisions the application role and database
(‘code_analysis’) from secrets.  No separate database-bootstrap command
is required.

8.2 casmgr-pg-set-password
==========================

Apply passwords from ‘/var/casmgr/secrets/.env’ to the running cluster.

   Default: updates superuser and application role (‘ALTER ROLE’).
Option ‘--superuser-only’ skips the application role.

   When rotating the superuser password, set
‘POSTGRES_SUPERUSER_CONNECT_PASSWORD’ to the current cluster password
for that run.

     sudo casmgr-pg-set-password
     sudo casmgr-pg-set-password --superuser-only

8.3 casmgr
==========

Daemon manager CLI (‘/usr/bin/casmgr’).  Wraps ‘systemctl’ and ‘docker’
for the all-in-one container; there is no host venv.

‘--config PATH’
     Config file (default ‘/etc/casmgr/config.json’ via
     ‘CASMGR_CONFIG’).
‘start’, ‘stop’, ‘restart’, ‘status’
     Manage the container through ‘systemctl casmgr.service’.
‘sessions’, ‘locks’
     List active client sessions and file locks (via ‘docker exec’).

   ‘casmgr’ dispatches host commands into the running container via
‘docker exec’.

     sudo casmgr --config /etc/casmgr/config.json status
     sudo casmgr --config /etc/casmgr/config.json restart

8.4 casmgr_ensure_instance_uuid
===============================

Python helper that ensures ‘registration.instance_uuid’ is a valid
UUID4.  Invoked from package ‘postinst’.


