11 Git and GitHub commands
**************************

The package exposes a project-scoped Git and GitHub command set through
MCP.  Agents should use these commands through the proxy instead of
running shell ‘git’ commands when the target repository is registered as
a casmgr project.  Every command resolves ‘project_id’ to the registered
project root; callers pass project-relative paths and refs, not host
working directories.

Invocation model
================

Use MCP proxy discovery first:

     list_servers
     list_projects
     call_server(server_id="code-analysis-server", copy_number=1,
                 command="<command>", params=project_id:<uuid>)

   Long-running or mutating Git commands may return ‘job_id’; poll
‘queue_get_job_status’ until ‘status’ is ‘completed’ or ‘failed’.  Treat
"queued" as submission only, not command success.  The final job payload
contains ‘command_success’, ‘inner_success’, and the command result.

Repository identity and config
==============================

‘git_config_get’
     Read one Git config key from ‘local’, ‘global’, or effective scope.
     Missing keys return ‘configured=false’ rather than failing.
‘git_config_list’
     List Git config entries, optionally with origin metadata.
‘git_identity_get’
     Return local and effective ‘user.name’ / ‘user.email’.
‘git_identity_set’
     Set ‘user.name’ and ‘user.email’.  Defaults to local repository
     config; global config requires an explicit ‘allow_global=true’.

   Use ‘git_identity_get’ before the first commit in a project.  Use
‘git_identity_set’ through MCP when identity is missing; do not repair
it by opening a shell on the host.

Read-only Git inspection
========================

‘git_status’
     Report current branch and porcelain-style status entries.
‘git_branch_current’
     Return current branch, upstream, ahead/behind, and detached state.
‘git_branch’
     Report local branch list with the current branch marked.
‘git_branch_list’
     Report local and remote branches with refs, commit ids, upstream,
     and scope.
‘git_branch_compare’
     Compare refs: ahead/behind, commits, and changed files.
‘git_branch_sync_status’
     Report whether a branch is synchronized with its upstream.
‘git_remote’
     List configured remotes.
‘git_log’
     Read commit history, optionally scoped to a revision or file.
‘git_show’
     Show one commit/object.
‘git_diff’
     Show diffs between refs or between a ref and the worktree.
‘git_blame’
     Show blame information for a file/range.

   These commands are the preferred first step before any mutating
action.  For an agent workflow, collect ‘git_status’,
‘git_branch_current’, and the relevant ‘git_diff’ before deciding how to
stage, commit, merge, or reset.

Branch and remote workflow
==========================

‘git_branch_create’
     Create a local branch, optionally checking it out.
‘git_branch_checkout’
     Switch branches; can create a branch from a start point.
‘git_branch_delete’
     Delete a local branch, with force support for cleanup branches.
‘git_branch_track_remote’
     Create or checkout a local branch tracking a remote branch.
‘git_branch_set_upstream’
     Set upstream tracking for the current or named branch.
‘git_branch_unset_upstream’
     Remove upstream tracking.
‘git_branch_fetch’
     Fetch a branch from a remote.
‘git_branch_pull’
     Pull one branch from a remote.
‘git_branch_push’
     Push one branch and optionally set upstream.
‘git_branch_delete_remote’
     Delete a remote branch.
‘git_remote_add’
     Add a local remote configuration entry without contacting the
     remote.
‘git_remote_set_url’
     Replace the fetch URL for an existing remote.
‘git_remote_set_push_url’
     Set a dedicated push URL while leaving the fetch URL unchanged.
‘git_remote_remove’
     Remove a local remote configuration entry; use ‘dry_run=true’ first
     when an agent is unsure.
‘git_remote_rename’
     Rename a local remote configuration entry.
‘git_fetch’
     Fetch from a remote.
‘git_pull’
     Pull the current branch.
‘git_push’
     Push the current or selected branch; supports dry-run workflows.
‘git_clone’
     Clone a remote repository into a watch directory and register the
     result as a new project.

   Normal branch workflow:

  1. ‘git_branch_current’ and ‘git_status’.
  2. ‘git_branch_create’ with ‘checkout=true’.
  3. Edit files through MCP file commands.
  4. ‘git_add’, ‘git_commit’.
  5. ‘git_branch_push’ or ‘git_push’.
  6. Use GitHub PR commands when a review flow is needed.

   Remote configuration rules:

   • Use ‘git_remote_add’, ‘git_remote_set_url’,
     ‘git_remote_set_push_url’, ‘git_remote_remove’, and
     ‘git_remote_rename’ to edit local ‘.git/config’ remote entries.
     These commands do not fetch, pull, push, or perform SSH
     authentication.
   • Run ‘git_remote’ before and after a remote configuration change
     when an audit trail is needed.
   • Do not pass inline credentials in remote URLs; configure
     authentication through the server's SSH or secret flow.

Working tree, index, and stash
==============================

‘git_add’
     Stage explicit paths, all changes, or tracked updates.
‘git_commit’
     Create or amend a commit from staged changes.
‘git_restore’
     Restore worktree paths and/or unstage paths.  Worktree restore can
     discard uncommitted content.
‘git_reset’
     Reset HEAD/index/worktree.  ‘mode=hard’ requires
     ‘confirm_hard=true’.
‘git_clean’
     Preview or delete untracked files.  Defaults to ‘dry_run=true’;
     deletion requires ‘confirm=true’.
‘git_stash_push’
     Save working-tree changes to stash, optionally scoped to paths.
‘git_stash_list’
     List stash entries.
‘git_stash_apply’
     Apply a stash entry, optionally keeping it.
‘git_stash_drop’
     Drop a stash entry.

   Safety rules:

   • Prefer explicit ‘paths’ for ‘git_add’, ‘git_restore’, ‘git_reset’,
     and ‘git_clean’.
   • Run ‘git_clean’ without ‘confirm=true’ first and inspect the
     dry-run output.
   • Use ‘git_reset mode=hard confirm_hard=true’ only after proving that
     no valuable worktree changes remain.

History surgery and integration
===============================

‘git_merge’
     Merge another ref into the current branch.  Supports ‘ff_only’,
     ‘no_ff’, ‘squash’, ‘commit=false’, messages, and ‘abort=true’.
‘git_rebase’
     Replay current or selected branch onto another base.  Supports
     ‘onto’, ‘autostash’, ‘abort’, ‘continue_rebase’, and ‘skip’.
     Interactive rebase is intentionally not exposed.
‘git_cherry_pick’
     Apply one or more commits.  Supports ‘no_commit’, ‘abort’, and
     ‘continue_pick’.
‘git_revert’
     Create inverse changes or commits.  Supports ‘no_commit’, merge
     ‘mainline’, ‘abort’, and ‘continue_revert’.
‘git_tag’
     List, create, delete, push, or delete remote tags.  Deletion
     requires ‘confirm_delete=true’; release tags should normally be
     annotated with ‘message’.

   Prefer ‘git_revert’ over ‘git_reset’ on shared branches.  Use
‘git_rebase’ primarily for unpublished local branches.  For
merge/rebase, conflicts are reported as command failures with Git
diagnostics in stderr; use status/diff commands plus MCP file editing to
resolve, then continue or abort.

Repository maintenance and safe automation
==========================================

The MCP Git layer includes administrative repository maintenance
commands so agents do not need a host shell when normal Git workflows
are blocked by stale locks, mixed ownership, or write-permission drift
in a registered project.

‘git_repo_permissions_check’
     Inspect ‘.git’, the working tree, or both for owner/group
     mismatches, missing write/search permissions, and effective CAS
     write access.  The command also performs short-lived write probes
     in the project root and ‘.git/objects’.
‘git_repo_permissions_repair’
     Repair owner/group and file modes for ‘.git’, the working tree, or
     both.  It defaults to ‘dry_run=true’; real changes require
     ‘confirm_repair=true’.  If files are owned by a user the CAS
     process cannot change, the command reports the exact paths and the
     required host-level repair.
‘git_repo_doctor’
     Produce one operational report: branch/status, stash list, stale
     lock candidates, permission report, and write probes.  Run this
     before a multi-step automation or after a failed pull/stash/commit.
‘git_repo_lock_cleanup’
     List or remove stale ‘.git/*.lock’ and ‘.git/**.lock’ files.
     Deletion requires ‘confirm_cleanup=true’; use ‘dry_run=true’ first.
‘git_pull_safe’
     Guarded pull workflow: capture status, stash dirty
     tracked/untracked work, pull the selected remote/ref, optionally
     apply the temporary stash, and optionally drop it after a clean
     apply.  The response is a step-by-step audit trail, not just a
     final success flag.

   Recommended recovery flow when ‘git_pull’, ‘git_stash_push’, or
‘git_commit’ fails with permission or lock diagnostics:

  1. Run ‘git_repo_doctor’.
  2. If permissions are dirty, run ‘git_repo_permissions_repair’ with
     ‘dry_run=true’; inspect planned actions.
  3. Run ‘git_repo_permissions_repair dry_run=false confirm_repair=true’
     only when the planned owner/group/mode changes are correct for the
     registered project.
  4. If stale locks remain, run ‘git_repo_lock_cleanup dry_run=true’;
     delete only confirmed stale locks.
  5. Prefer ‘git_pull_safe’ over manually composing
     stash/pull/apply/drop when updating a dirty server checkout from a
     remote branch.

   These commands are project-scoped and use ‘project_id’; they never
accept a host working directory.  Their full JSON schemas, return
contracts, error cases, and examples are included in *note Command
reference: Command reference.

GitHub operations
=================

‘github_repo_get’
     Read one repository.
‘github_repo_list’
     List repositories visible to the configured GitHub token.
‘github_pr_list’
     List pull requests.
‘github_pr_get’
     Read one pull request in detail.
‘github_pr_create’
     Create a pull request.
‘github_pr_merge’
     Merge a pull request.
‘github_issue_list’
     List issues.
‘github_issue_create’
     Create an issue.
‘github_issue_comment’
     Add an issue or pull-request comment.
‘github_release_create’
     Create a GitHub release.

   GitHub commands use the configured token and repository parameters.
Read-only commands are safe for discovery.  Write commands create public
repository state; agents should only execute them when the requested
outcome explicitly includes a PR, issue, comment, merge, or release.

Coverage boundary
=================

The Git/GitHub command set is sufficient for normal repository work
without a terminal: inspect, branch, edit through MCP file commands,
stage, commit, stash, sync, push, create PRs/issues/releases, merge,
rebase, cherry-pick, revert, tag, reset, and clean.  ‘git worktree’ is
intentionally not part of this block yet because it commonly creates
directories outside the registered project root; it needs an explicit
allowed-path policy before being exposed safely.


